body:
### 🐛 Current behavior

When implementing search results with React InstantSearch hooks, specifically the `useInstantSearch` hook, there's a behavior with the initial render sequence.

- During initialization, the library creates artificial results with empty hits.
- The status is set to `idle` during this initialization phase
- With empty hits and an "idle" status, a caller can assume that the search is complete, thus rendering an empty results message to the user.
- Only after initialization does the status change to `loading`, and the results are filled.

This behavior appears to be intentional based on the [test suite](https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/blob/master/packages/react-instantsearch-core/src/hooks/__tests__/useInstantSearch.test.tsx). However, it's a bit counterintuitive and can lead to unexpected behavior.

If I'm mistaken in my assumption that this could cause unintential behavior, please let me know. Otherwise, I've set up a PR that may address this.

### 🔍 Steps to reproduce

Create a function that uses `useInstantSearch` for the search status context:

```tsx
function InfiniteHits<T extends BaseHit>(props: UseInfiniteHitsProps<T>) {
  const { items } = useInfiniteHits<T>(props);
  const { status } = useInstantSearch<T>();

  if (status === "loading") {
    console.log("loading");
    return (
      <div className="flex h-96 items-center justify-center">
        <Loader2 className="h-10 w-10 animate-spin" />
      </div>
    );
  }

  if (items.length === 0) {
    console.log("no results");
    return (
      <div className="flex h-96 items-center justify-center">
        <p className="text-muted-foreground text-lg">No results found</p>
      </div>
    );
  }

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-4">
      {items.map((item) => (
        <div key={item.objectID}>
          <h3>{item.title}</h3>
          <p>{item.description}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

After using this inside the `InstantSearch` component, the `no results` message will be logged before the `loading` message, thus resulting in a flash of the `no results found` to the user.

### Live reproduction

https://codesandbox.io/p/sandbox/gifted-dawn-wgvp76

### 💭 Expected behavior

I'd expect the idle state to be preceded by the loading state, or have a `init` state for the initialization process

### Package version

react-instantsearch@7.15.4

### Operating system

Linux 6.12.17-1-lts

### Browser

Mozilla Zen 1.8.2b

